◆ MappingQ()

* This class implements the functionality for polynomial mappings [2.x.0] of polynomial degree [2.x.1] that will be used on all cells of the mesh The MappingQ1 and MappingQ classes specialize this behavior slightly* The class is poorly named It should really have been called MappingQ because it consistently uses [2.x.2] mappings on all cells of a triangulation the name MappingQ was already taken when we rewrote the entire class hierarchy for mappings One might argue that one should always use MappingQGeneric over the existing class MappingQ ( which  ,

only uses mappings of  degree[2.x.3][1.x.0] 
)

◆ hexahedra()

* This class implements the functionality for polynomial mappings [2.x.0] of polynomial degree [2.x.1] that will be used on all cells of the mesh The MappingQ1 and MappingQ classes specialize this behavior slightly* The class is poorly named It should really have been called MappingQ because it consistently uses [2.x.2] mappings on all cells of a triangulation the name MappingQ was already taken when we rewrote the entire class hierarchy for mappings One might argue that one should always use MappingQGeneric over the existing class there are good reasons to use MappingQ in many curved domains are only provided with information about how exactly edges at the boundary are but we do not know anything about internal edges in the absence of other we can only assume that internal edges are straight and in that case internal cells may as well be treated is bilinear quadrilaterals or trilinear hexahedra ( An example of how such meshes look is shown in  already[2.x.4],
but it is also discussed in the "Results" section  of .[2.x.5] 
)
